{{ill|Utsushihikanasaku|ja|宇都志日金拆命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Utsushihikanasaku|qq=}} (宇都志日金拆命) is a Japanese deity, son of [[Watatsumi]] and the {{ill|Oyagami|simple|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Oyagami|qq=}} or tutelary deity of the [[Azumi people]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://historyofjapan.co.uk/wiki/utsushihikanasaku/ | title=Utsushihikanasaku • . A History . . Of Japan . 日本歴史|qq=draft|qq=draft}}</ref><ref name="explore-azumino-2023a">{{Cite web |title=Explore Azumino! - Hotaka Shrine |url=https://azumino-e-tabi.net/en/sightseeing/hotaka-shrine |access-date=2023-12-06 |website=Explore Azumino! |publisher=[[Japan Tourism Agency]] |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name="https-2">https://www.mlit.go.jp/tagengo-db/common/001562761.pdf</ref><ref name="hikes in japan">{{Cite web |date=2020-10-01 |title=Mt. Hotaka also have deities enshrined, and these deities are as their tutelaries : JINJA-GAKU 3 {{!}} HIKES IN JAPAN |url=https://hikesinjapan.yamakei-online.com/topics/jinjagaku03.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201001062231/https://hikesinjapan.yamakei-online.com/topics/jinjagaku03.php |archive-date=2020-10-01 |access-date=2023-12-06}}</ref>
[[original pages]]

He is also known by the name Hotakami no Mikoto.<ref name="explore-azumino-2023a" /><ref name="https-2" /><ref name="hikes in japan" /> He is said to have descended to earth on the nearby [[Mount Hotakadake]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Kamikochi - A Place of Special Importance |url=https://www.snowmonkeyresorts.com/activities/kamikochi/a-place-of-special-importance |access-date=2023-12-06 |website=SNOW MONKEY RESORTS}}</ref>

He is considered the ancestor of the [[Azumi people]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ofune Matsuri – A Unique Festival in Nagano, Japan! - Festivals & Events｜COOL JAPAN VIDEOS｜A Website With Information About Travel, Culture, Food, History, and Things to Do in Japan |url=https://cooljapan-videos.com/en/articles/au3wf7b2 |access-date=2023-12-06 |website=cooljapan-videos.com |language=en}}</ref> [[Azumi-no-isora]] is also considered an ancestral deity of them, but has a different name and myth.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a0QKAQAAMAAJ&q=Azumi-no-isora |title=Japanese Journal of Religious Studies |publisher=International Institute for the Study of Religions |year=1993}}</ref>

He is worshipped at {{ill|Hotaka Shrine|simple|4=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hotaka Shrine|qq=}}.<ref name="explore-azumino-2023a" /><ref name="https-2" /> In the central Honden.<ref name="explore-azumino-2023a" /> It is a prominent [[Myojin Taisha]]<ref name="nussbaum178">[[Louis-Frédéric|Nussbaum, Louis-Frédéric]]. (2005). [https://books.google.com/books?id=p2QnPijAEmEC&pg=PA178&dq= "''Engi-shiki''"] in ''Japan Encyclopedia'', p. 178.</ref>.<ref name="explore-azumino-2023a" /> An agricultural shrine in [[Azumino]] used by Azumi people who moved inland to become farmers..<ref name="explore-azumino-2023a" /><ref name="https-2" /> which also worships his father [[Watatsumi]].<ref name="explore-azumino-2023a" /><ref name="https-2" /><ref name="hikes in japan" />

